### Polymorphism in C#

Polymorphism (many forms) allows objects of different types to respond to the same method call in their own way.

### Compile-Time vs Runtime Polymorphism

| Type | Mechanism | Example |
|------|-----------|---------|
| Compile-time | Method overloading | `Add(int, int)` vs `Add(double, double)` |
| Runtime | Method overriding | `virtual` / `override` |

### Runtime Polymorphism with virtual/override

```csharp
public class Animal
{
    public virtual void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

public class Dog : Animal
{
    public override void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Dog barks");
    }
}

public class Cat : Animal
{
    public override void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Cat meows");
    }
}
```

### Polymorphic Behavior

```csharp
Animal[] animals = { new Dog(), new Cat(), new Animal() };

foreach (Animal a in animals)
{
    a.MakeSound();  // Each calls its own implementation
}
// Output:
// Dog barks
// Cat meows
// Animal makes a sound
```

### Method Hiding (new keyword)

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public void Display() { Console.WriteLine("Base"); }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public new void Display() { Console.WriteLine("Derived"); }
}

// Usage
Base obj = new Derived();
obj.Display();  // "Base" (not polymorphic)
```

### Polymorphism with Interfaces

```csharp
interface IShape
{
    double GetArea();
}

class Circle : IShape { public double GetArea() => Math.PI * 4; }
class Square : IShape { public double GetArea() => 25; }

IShape[] shapes = { new Circle(), new Square() };
foreach (var s in shapes)
    Console.WriteLine(s.GetArea());
```

### Benefits of Polymorphism

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Extensibility | Add new types without changing existing code |
| Maintainability | Centralized behavior in base class |
| Flexibility | Program to interfaces, not implementations |
| Code reuse | Common interface for different types |

### Polymorphism with Abstract Classes

```csharp
public abstract class Shape
{
    public abstract double GetArea();
}

public class Circle : Shape
{
    public override double GetArea() => Math.PI * Radius * Radius;
}
```

> **Key Point:** Runtime polymorphism requires `virtual` in the base class and `override` in derived classes. The correct method is determined at runtime based on the actual object type, not the variable type. This enables writing flexible, extensible code.

### Pattern Matching with Polymorphism

```csharp
foreach (Animal a in animals)
{
    if (a is Dog dog)
        dog.Bark();
    else if (a is Cat cat)
        cat.Meow();
}

